{"timestamp": "2025-12-03 09:44:28.249937", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — current network state\n\nSummary\n- Overall network reachability is healthy. Hosts in the 10.<core>.<dist>.0/24 spaces can reach central infrastructure (DNS, DHCP, load‑balancer, and the published web servers) with no packet loss and modest RTTs.\n- One class of connectivity appears abnormal on the reachability scan: the backend web servers (20.200.0.2–.4) could not be verified as able to reach host subnets (status \"unknown\" in the scan). This behavior matches the documented design intent that backend servers must not be directly reachable by hosts, and the topology shows those backends are only connected to the load‑balancer, not to the server access router. The isolation appears to be intentional rather than a failure.\n\nObserved evidence (from reachability scan)\n- Infrastructure and published web services reachable from hosts:\n  - dns_server = 10.200.0.2 — pings to sample hosts: 0% loss; RTTs ~2–4 ms.\n  - dhcp_server = 10.200.0.8 — 0% loss; RTTs ~2–6 ms.\n  - load_balancer = 10.200.0.7 — 0% loss to tested hosts; RTTs ~2–3 ms.\n  - web_server_0..3 = 10.200.0.3..10.200.0.6 — 0% loss; RTTs in low ms.\n  - Many inter‑host pings across areas show 0% loss and expected RTT ranges (1–7 ms), indicating stable L2/L3 forwarding and routing.\n- Backend web hosts (internal/backends):\n  - backend_web_0 = 20.200.0.2, backend_web_1 = 20.200.0.3, backend_web_2 = 20.200.0.4\n  - Ping tests with these as sources to representative hosts (e.g., host_2_3_2_1 / host_2_3_4_1) returned status \"unknown\" in the scan results (no TX/RX/loss data recorded by the probe).\n  - No other infrastructure showed signs of loss or route flapping in the collected results.\n\nLocalization (devices/subnets implicated)\n- Affected / isolated devices: backend_web_0, backend_web_1, backend_web_2 (20.200.0.0/24).\n- All other named devices in the topology (server_access_router, web_server_0..3 [10.200.0.3–.6], load_balancer [10.200.0.7], dns_server [10.200.0.2], dhcp_server [10.200.0.8], access switches and hosts) show normal reachability based on the probe results.\n\nRoot cause analysis\n- The backend web servers live in the 20.200.0.0/24 network and are only connected to the load_balancer per the provided topology ((load_balancer:eth1, backend_web_0:eth0), etc.). They do not appear on the server_access_router-facing 10.200.0.0/24 network.\n- The reachability probe could not obtain ping results from the backend hosts to representative client hosts (status \"unknown\"). This is consistent with the backends being isolated on a separate management/internal network (20.200.0.0/24) that is not advertised or routed toward the host subnets — i.e., there is no path from hosts to backends, and/or the probe tool could not reach them because they have no route to those hosts.\n- The isolation of 20.200.0.0/24 and absence of direct routing/advertisement for it (or purposeful firewalling/ACLs) is the likely root cause of the backends being unreachable from hosts. This matches the stated design goal: backend web servers must not be directly accessible by hosts; front‑end access to the service must go through web99.local (the Nginx load balancer).\n- No anomalies were observed in OSPF/DHCP/DNS reachability from the provided data (these services responded, and routes appear to be functioning end‑to‑end for published servers).\n\nOther observations / notes\n- RTTs and loss to core infra (DNS, DHCP, web servers, load balancer) are low and stable, indicating working IP routing/OSPF advertisement for the 10.200.0.0/24 server farm and host subnets.\n- The only items that test as non‑reachable (or unknown) are the backend web instances in 20.200.0.0/24; given the topology and stated design, this is expected behavior rather than an operational fault.\n- The \"unknown\" status for backend->host pings in the get_reachability output suggests the probe from the backend source either could not be executed or returned no replies; combined with topology it indicates no L3 path exists between backend network and host networks (or it is intentionally blocked).\n\nConclusion\n- Network health for hosts, distribution, core, and the published server farm (10.200.0.0/24), including DNS, DHCP, load‑balancer and front‑end web servers, is good based on reachability tests: no packet loss and sensible RTT values.\n- The only apparent connectivity anomaly is the inability to reach or validate backend web servers on 20.200.0.0/24 from host subnets. This is consistent with the intended isolation of backend servers (they are only attached to the load balancer), and therefore does not indicate an unintended failure in the observed data set.\n\nIf you want, I can run targeted checks next (examples):\n- ping/load tests from the load_balancer to each backend_web to confirm internal backend reachability and latency,\n- show routing/OSPF adjacency and route tables on server_access_router and core routers to confirm which networks are advertised,\n- or attempt an explicit ping from a host to a backend IP to confirm the host‑to‑backend path is blocked/absent.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 32544, "output_tokens": 2366, "total_tokens": 34910, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 2688}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1088}}}
